<section class="guideSection">
  <h2>What Garden Sensors Actually Do</h2>

  <p>
    Sensors measure conditions like soil moisture, temperature, or humidity and send that information to you.
  </p>

  <p>
    For vacation watering, the most useful metric is:
  </p>

  <ul class="plainList">
    <li><strong>soil moisture</strong></li>
  </ul>

  <p>
    This tells you whether your plants are getting enough water.
  </p>
</section>

<section class="guideSection">
  <h2>Why Soil Moisture Matters Most</h2>

  <p>
    Other readings are useful, but soil moisture directly reflects plant conditions.
  </p>

  <p>
    It helps you:
  </p>

  <ul class="plainList">
    <li>detect watering failures</li>
    <li>monitor system performance</li>
    <li>decide whether intervention is needed</li>
  </ul>

  <p>
    It’s the most actionable data point.
  </p>
</section>

<section class="guideSection">
  <h2>What Makes a Good Vacation Sensor</h2>

  <h3>Reliable Readings</h3>
  <p>
    Consistency matters more than precision.
  </p>

  <h3>Remote Access</h3>
  <p>
    Allows you to check conditions while away.
  </p>

  <h3>Simple Interface</h3>
  <p>
    Data should be easy to interpret quickly.
  </p>

  <h3>Stable Connectivity</h3>
  <p>
